It was a very hot day and we were sweating before the meals came out.

The service was good, it had a homely vibe. As soon as you walk in the door you're greeted and told to sit wherever you like.

I ordered the Rayos Special and OMG it was delicious!  Two stuffed chicken enchiladas with green sauce, refried beans, and home fried potatoes topped with an over hard egg. The green sauce was delicious and the flavor combination with the chicken, tortilla, sauce,  and egg was delicious.  My potatoes were under cooked though

My husband ordered french toast, sausage, and eggs scrambled soft. He said the flavor of the french toast was very tasty but it was too soft and his soft scrambled eggs were hard. He also said the sausage links had a crunchy texture as if they had been deep fried. He said they were really tasty.

My meal alone would make me want to go back but if they dont resolve that AC situation we just cant until the weather changes.< /text><user_id>102380136950880313877</user_id><name>Markisha Williams< /name>< Rating>

< time>
1622327280568<//time>
<Name>Bruno Moura<//Name><user>101456495175867903253</user></record></dataset><record>
<gmap_id>0x80c2bbb7c29ed5c5:0x30a1737c1f8b8474<//gmap_id><review>This park is walking distance from my residence, just across the 10 freeway. I'm somewhat reticent to add my thoughts about it because I cherish this location and not simply because it's conveniently nearby. Just to properly explain: I worry some readers may be turned away from the park when I mention a couple less desirable details, while others who appreciate my candor could overrun the little recreation center with new visitors!

I'm sure it's all me fretting needlessly over a trivial matter...

Aside from being conveniently located in the same parking lot as the Rancho Park Public Library and sitting across from the Notre Dame Catholic School, it is within walking distance from a handful of other useful places (aside from my own home). A couple gas stations, 7-11, Trader Joe's, Winchell's, the 10 freeway on-ramps(WB leads immediately to the 405 interchange as well) and a handful of other small points of interest can all be reached through a less-than-tiring trek on foot for an average adult.

The recreation center itself is a small hub of public buildings offering restrooms to visitors during operating hours along with a plethora of programs and services available to patrons. I believe daycare, adult education, excercise classes, outreach services for victims of homelessness and other social services may be enlisted there. I'm not certain exactly what or how many of these things are actually offered, especially during the pandemic protocols, but for others living nearby it is certainly worth a visit during business hours to find out.

My personal endorsement of this locale originates from the enjoyment and relaxation I've been able to find in the relatively large park area. Yes, many other parks may be bigger or have more resources to partake in, but the Palms Recreation Center has a large grass area the size of a football field, a little league diamond I have never actually seen anyone use but is nonetheless far from disrepair, a decent size seating area with a dozen or so picnic tables/benches on a concrete slab for picnickers, partyers or barbeque lovers(a couple Qs are also located near the picnic benches built into the slab) two full-court basketball courts of adult regulation size with bleachers, a group of a half-dozen or so excercise machines built to scale resistance with an adult's weight and a decent sized playground area for younger children with swings, slides and a few more benches and tables for onlooking parents.

There are often a decent amount of patrons during daylight hours, especially on weekends. Some of the park's regulars come from a "private residence-challenged" demographic, *ahem*, but I have never found any such folks to be rude, loud, overtly intoxicated or unruly in any way. In my experience, they maintain a healthy symbiosis with the Recreation Center's position as a place that families and children and pets even patronize.

Other unfortunate details include the fact that it IS located near the freeway on a major thoroughfare (Overland Ave.), both pro and con in my opinion, the Metro train also borders the park area opposite the street, and at any given time a half-dozen or more stray cats make their home in the area around the park as well. Much like the other park goers lacking a committed traditional home or family, these cats have never been obtrusive, rabid, malicious or anything offensive other than sad and unfortunate.

I can only dream of what the world would be if our great industrial civilization could actually solve the social detritus and broken beings it seems to callously create and cast-off in unconcerned, never-endlessly recurring cycles....but instead of getting stuck in your head with vague fears and unresolved worries, try visiting the Palms Recreation Center if you're nearby!<//review>< rate>
4<//rate>
<date>1613599828232< /date>< Pics>

<Review>I'm sorry to say not good. I have been in Manteca since 1984. This place has been an Italian restaurant the entire time. We loved it when it was Pietros enjoyed it when it was Dave and Sylvia's. During this time Manteca obtained many more options and the restaurant in the Cardoza Center fell off our radar. We were in the neighborhood looking for a place to eat and decided to give Angelenos a try. We both had pasta dishes Chicken Parmesan for myself Shrimp and scallops Alfredo. The chicken was not pounded and the sauce had no flavor. My dish again flavorless and completely lacked the richness you'd expect from an Alfredo sauce. The decor is exactly the same and was out dated in the early 80s. Our server was attentive enough since we were the only ones in there but he was dressed in Jeans, flannel shirt and a baseball style hat. We probably will not be back.</Review>< Pics>

<review>Absolutely the best customer service and SUPER YUMMY food!!! This past weekend my son's 3rd party was scheduled to be at a local park, because of weather we were forced to move the party indoors. I already had 60 RSVP's so I didn‚Äôt want to have it in my home. Angelano's allowed us to use their private room, catered the event and their customer service is impeccable!!!! I was so impressed, they are very thoughtful, they arranged the room so there was enough room to move around, room to play games, they allowed us to decorate and were thoroughly accommodating. The food???? OMG the food was sooooooooo good! The put out a yummy salad bar so everyone could pick what they wanted on their salad (perfect for little ones), I had suggested spaghetti with meat sauce and fettuccini Alfredo for the pastas and the owner made penne with meat sauce and spirals with alfredo and chicken (MUCH better for little ones) AND he surprised us and made some mac and cheese too!!!! Their bread was AMAZING and I was just so impressed overall. I will definitely be back for their food, I'm a foodie, I LOVE FOOD and it takes a lot to impress me. Their food was fresh, flavorful and delicious.  I heard they make a mean burger too. If you are having a party in Manteca / Lathrop / Ripon check out Angelano's!!!! <rating>5<//rating>< review>
I had been trying to get the TCU for my 04 Rubicon for almost a year, started out sending the original off for rebuild, it came back not rebuildable. and the company did not have a replacement.  I searched for several weeks for another supplier, was actually told by the Napa Dealer that the only place in the country that could rebuild them was Cardone in New Jersey.  So did not have much hope, I found a place online in Florida that said he had one on the shelf ready to go and it could be mine for $900.00, I told him to keep it.  I was referred to Flagship One in New York by the local Jeep Dealer.  So I contacted them, they had one on the shelf ready to ship,  would ship in 3-5 days, after a week of waiting I contacted them and I was told it was in programming and would ship soon.  This went on for 11 weeks. By chance I found ARES Technologies, I called and of course with everything I had been through over the past year I was skeptical when I was told they had one, plug and play ready, and it would ship the following morning.  I gave the young lady the fifth degree, until I was pretty sure I was not being taken advantage of. So I placed the order and BAM! there it was 3 days later.  Unfortunately (no fault on Ares Part) I installed the part the same day, started it up and 0 Oil pressure. I had to have it towed to the shop and have it checked out. Evidently because it had sat for a Year while trying to find this part the Oil Pump lost prime, so I ended up having a new oil pump installed. I picked it up from the shop and have been driving it ever since.  Oh and the best part is, I got the part for less than what I had paid at Flagship One.
THANK YOU  ARES TECHNOLOGIES FOR YOUR OUTSTANDING CUSTOMER SERVICE.  I have contacted that JEEP dealership and told them not to ever send anyone to FS1 anymore but to Make sure that they Send their customers to ARES Technologies.</review>

i bought this item because this was cheaper than going to the dealer to reflash my ECM. i looked at the website and i even called and asked them about the item. i thought all i had to do was plug, play, and relearn the key. i was not informed that i had to do something with the crankshaft position relearn? which required a GM tech 2. it defeats the purpose of me not going to the dealer. because it required me to go to the dealer to have it learned. the price for both (flash and relearn) was the same. i returned it. no problem. but i had to pay for return shipping??!! if you told me in the beginning i needed this i wouldnt have bought it and just bit the bullet and went to the dealer. horrible!<//Text>
<pictures>None</pictures><response>{'time': 1594997383632, 'text': "Our dear customer,\nWe are sorry to hear that you were not satisfied with our service. Here at ARES Technologies we prioritize our customers' needs but we also have certain policies to follow and would like our customers to respect what we have agreed upon. We would like to use this opportunity to explain what occured and hope it clarifies your concern.\n1. The cost of purchasing the module and having it flashed at a delaership would exceed $500, you purchased the module at about a $100 and we provided the key relearn instruction to have your car started.\n2. The crankshaft relearn requirement after swapping the PCM is based on GM engineering design and it is beyond our control. In certain cars manufactured by GM company you need to perform this relearn to make your new PCM aware of the position of the crankshaft sensor. It is a 5 second process and needs to be done by a scan tool.\n3. The fact that your local dealership decided to charge you $100 for a 5 second relearn process is beyond our control. That's why we always encourage our customers to consult with a local mechanic or auto electrician before taking their cars to a dealership.\n4. We accepted your request to return the part and we didn't charge you any restocking fee as we are the only business in this industry that won't charge our customers any form of restocking or programming fee for the first 30 days after purchasing the module.\n5. Our return policy in our website clearly states that it is the customer's responsibility to return the part if they decide to do that for any reason.\nWe wish you the best and have a great day!"}< /response><gmap_id>0x80dcb7cf016485a7:0xd49b2058b61e2cb3< /gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
